# 2p_slope_pose — host. Pairs with 2p_slope_pose.client.shot.
#
# Verifies the fix for the user-reported pose desync between own
# window and other-client window when a mech stands on a slope:
# pre-fix the LOCAL mech's bones got pushed out of the slope poly
# by physics_constrain_and_collide (which gates on inv_mass>0), then
# pose_compute wrote straight-down targets that the swept-test
# clipped to the slope surface — feet visibly on the slope. The
# REMOTE mech on the OTHER client has inv_mass=0, so the collide
# pass skipped it; pose_compute wrote the same straight-down targets
# but they landed inside the slope poly with no push-out — body
# rendered in a static straight-legged pose, feet inside the slope.
#
# Fix: physics_push_mech_out_of_terrain runs AFTER pose_write for
# every alive mech (ignoring inv_mass). Both views now show the
# same bone-on-slope-surface pose.
#
# Map: aurora has a 30° west hill that rises eastward from world
# (640, 2752) at the floor up to (1024, 2528) at the peak. Both
# mechs spawn on the rising slope so the pose desync (if any)
# shows up clearly against the black sky.

window 1280 720
out build/shots/net/2p_slope_pose_host
network host 24197
name HostA
loadout - "Pulse Rifle" "Sidearm" Light Standard
map aurora

# Host stands part-way up the west hill, client further up — far
# enough apart that BOTH mechs are clearly visible in each client's
# window (the camera follows the local mech, with ~150-200 px of
# horizontal gap between the two). Pelvis y values are above the
# slope surface so each mech falls into place during the first few
# ticks (slope surface at host's x=750 is y≈2688; at client's
# x=900 it's y≈2600).
spawn_at 750 2620
peer_spawn 1 900 2540
aim 900 2540

# Let physics settle.
at  60 shot t060_settled
at 120 shot t120_settled
at 200 shot t200_settled

at 280 end
